  and Flag of 
  <a href="de-od-03.html#wb">Wesenberg</a>, Germany (fotw)</em>
  </dd>

  <hr/><a name="bendwise"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">BENDWISE (or BENDWISE SINISTER)</dt>
  <dd>1) In traditional heraldry see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvi2.html#inbend">in bend</a>&rsquo;
   and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvi2.html#inbendsinister">in bend sinister</a>&rsquo;.<br>
   2) In some heraldic usage this term relates specifically to the axis of a charge or charges, 
   rather than to its, or their position, on a shield, a banner of arms or a flag � but see 
   &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvi2.html#inbend">in bend</a>&rsquo;
   and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvi2.html#inbendsinister">in bend sinister</a>&rsquo; as referenced above.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2851.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2851.gif" alt="bendwise example" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2852.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2852.gif" alt="bendwise example" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d479.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d479.gif" alt="Eiken CH" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br /><em>Flag of <a href="fr-68.html">Haut Rhin</a>, France (fotw); Flag of 
  <a href="ch-vd146.html">Le Sentier</a>, Switzerland (fotw); Flag of <a href="ch-ag114.html">Eiken</a>, Switzerland (fotw)</em>
  </dd>

  <hr /><a name="bendy"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">BENDY</dt>
  <dd>1) The heraldic term for the division of a shield, a banner of arms or any quartering 
  thereof, into four or more usually (but not invariably) equal bends or bendlets, 
  and running from the upper dexter to the lower sinister in alternating 
  tinctures � but see &lsquo;<a href="#bend">bend</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvm5.html#multistripe">multi-stripe</a>&rsquo; 
  (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-b.html#bannerofarms">banner of arms</a>&rsquo;, &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd1.html#dexter">dexter</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-q.html#quartering">quartering 1)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs4.html#sinister">sinister</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt1.html#tincture">tincture</a>&rsquo;).   
  <br>2) See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-w.html#wavy">wavy</a>&rsquo;. 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d969.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d969.gif" alt="bendy" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d970.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d970.gif" alt="&Scaron;marje pri Jel&scaron;ah" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d970a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d970a.gif" alt="&Scaron;marje pri Jel&scaron;ah" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br><em>Example; Flag and Arms of <a href="si-124.html">&Scaron;marje pri Jel&scaron;ah</a>, Slovenia (fotw)</em><hr /><a name="bendysinister"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">BENDY SINISTER</dt>
  <dd>The heraldic term for the division of a shield, a banner of arms or any quartering 
  thereof, into four or more usually (but not invariably) equal bends or bendlets, and 
  running from the lower dexter to the upper sinister in alternating tinctures &ndash; but see 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp3.html#perbendsinister">per bend sinister</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvm5.html#multistripe">multi-stripe</a>&rsquo; 
  (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-b.html#bannerofarms">banner of arms</a>&rsquo;, &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd1.html#dexter">dexter</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-q.html#quartering">quartering 1)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs4.html#sinister">sinister</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt1.html#tincture">tincture</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d972.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d972.gif" alt="Wasseramt" border="0" height="108" /></a>&nbsp;
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d971.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d971.gif" alt="bendy sinister" border="0" height="108" /></a>&nbsp;
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2928.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2928.gif" alt="Tr�llikon" border="0" height="108" /></a><br>
  <em>Flag of <a href="ch-so-wa.html">Wasseramt</a>, Switzerland (fotw);
  Example; Flag of <a href="ch-zh034.html">Tr�llikon</a>, Switzerland (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="bent"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">BENT </dt>
  <dd>In heraldry see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-e.html#embowed">embowed</a>&rsquo;.  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d740b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d740b.gif" alt="Bent" border="0" height="108" /></a>
